column41: This frilly was disputing our access to the sandpit in the playground. The frill-necked lizard is so called because of the large ruff of skin which usually lies folded back against its head and neck. The neck frill is supported by long spines of cartilage which are connected to the jaw bones. When the lizard is frightened, it gapes its mouth, exposing a bright pink or yellow lining; the frill flares out as well, displaying bright orange and red scales. This reaction is often used to discourage predators or during courtship. The lizard is a member of the agamid family. It a relatively large lizard, growing up to 91.4 cm. The lizard is also capable of bipedal locomotion, that is they run on their hind legs only.

The Frilled Lizard (Chlamydosaurus kingii) is the sole member of its genus. It is very distinctive with a loose frill of scaly skin attached to the neck. At rest it folds like a cape over the neck and shoulders; erect it stands upright to encircle its head and neck. NT and WA lizards have a red or orange frill while those from Q’ld are grey. Spends most of its time in trees; when on the ground it will run erect on its hind legs.

dark tip of tail. lighter through the body. white patch between the face and frill.
dark coloured lizard was on the road but ran up a tree after. has a large frill around the neck it shows when in danger
a lizard with a frill it puffs out when it feels threatened

QUEST SPECIES MIXED BAG - GLADSTONECool water dragon running across the road, running on its back legs only front feet and head up in the air. About 25 cm long head to tail i guess, Grey, but light colored stripes on its tail. Could not get close cause very shy. Looks like "frills" around its neck.
smaller frilled necked lizard than we typically see in this area.
Found in the middle of the road near Litchfield National Park standing on its hind legs
initially I thought it was a stick when it was sunning itself. as ot moved I could see it's frill although it didn't display it fully.
Quite a large lizard. Close 1m long. Sheltering from the rain.
large dragon, great tree climber, great camouflage
juvenile lizard safely release onto a tree. has a small frill
Chillin in the niddle of the road until we drove up, then he tried to see the car off qith his frill!
On the side of the road then ran up a tree
Hanging out on a floodway sign, Cooinda, Kakadu National Park.
young frilled neck eating a spider
on road not keen to get off
young frilled necked lizard. around 8cm. First one I have seen since march.
Two of them on trees next to each other
the king!! lizard with a frill around its neck
Fully grown one, ran across the road and climbed way up into a tree. Gulf country, east of Borroloola.
Large lizard with a frilly neck collar up a gum tree at Harding’s Paddock. Quest: Brisbane Ipswich mega quest

Found this (approx 70 cm) dinosaur just chilling on a tree. A large frill around the neck, orange body which fades to a more yellow colour towards the tail and two whiteish cheeks. Very happy to see this big lizard as they were almost wiped out a few years ago. I'm so excited for this rare lizard I used my gold coin.
this lizard was on the road and didn't care too much I was there. he walked past the car and down into the bush but it was like a slow run using only his back two legs to slowly hop side to side
